When construct an available_package object we append the dependency
constraints to the dependencies member as a special type of dependency. Note
that we already have the type member (optional<test_dependency_type> type)
which we could extend, adding the constraint type.

Handle dependency constraints as the regular dependencies, with the following
differences:

- Before the enabled dependency constraint is considered for collecting, check
  if the dependency is in the dependency tree (see below for the notes on the
  dependency tree).

- After all packages are collected (right before the collect_dependents()
  call), check all the enabled dependency constraints if the presence of the
  constrained dependency in the dependency tree didn't change since the moment
  the constrain was collected/denied to collect. If it differs, then add the
  record to the dependent_dependency_constraints map to consider the correct
  (final) containment state on the next re-collection and throw an exception
  (derived from scratch_collection) to re-collect. If on some of the
  subsequent re-collections it turns out that the map entry was used but it
  doesn't match the final dependency tree containment, then update the entry
  and throw the exception to re-collect. Watch out for yo-yoing.

  Note that checking for the dependency containment during collection is
  tricky and probably not exactly cheap (see below for the notes on the
  dependency tree). Also it can be quite a burden to maintain this check
  implementation in sync with pkg_configure*() functions.

  Actually, maybe it is easier and more reliable to initially always assume
  that the dependency is not contained in the tree. After the plan simulation
  we could check for that and if the assumption was wrong, then save this
  knowledge in the dependent_dependency_constraints map and re-collect using
  this knowledge on the subsequent iterations. Somehow this approach feels
  preferable.

- When the package is being configured, the dependency constraint is resolved
  to the selected package in the same way as for a regular dependency but the
  'constrains=true' flag is saved into the respective prerequisite_info
  value. But first need to make sure that the dependency is really in the
  dependency tree (may not be the case due to the wrong containment assumption
  at the time of the constraint collection, etc). A dependency constraint
  prerequisite (constrains==true) can be handled differently from a regular
  prerequisite in some situations:

  - Do not add config.import.* variable to the dependent for such prerequisite.

  - evaluate_dependency() do not consider the dependent's repository when
    searches for the available packages. It can ignore such prerequisites
    while calculating the dependency's used/unused status. In fact, if such a
    prerequisite is present in the dependent, then the constrained dependency
    is used by definition (since it is in the dependency tree).

  In other situations such prerequisites are handled uniformly with the
  regular prerequisites:

  - evaluate_dependency() also uses their version constraints.

  - query_existing_dependents() also returns dependents for them.

Notes:

- Dependency tree during collection contains both collected and configured
  uncollected dependencies. For example:

  configured: libbar/1.0 -> libbiz/1.0 -> libbuz/1.0 -> libbaz/1.0

  manifests:

  foo/1.0 depends on libfoo/1.0 depends on libbar/1.0
  foo/1.0 constrains libbaz
  biz/2.0 depends on libbiz/2.0 depends on libbuz

  $ bpkg build foo biz

  Dependency tree for foo during collection after biz is recursively collected:

  foo/1.0 (new, collected)                                       ->
    libfoo/1.0 (new, collected)                                  ->
      libbar/1.0 (configured, not yet collected for reconfigure) ->
        libbiz/2.0 (upgrade, collected)                          ->
          libbuz/1.0 (configured, collected non recursively)     ->
            libbaz/1.0 (configured, not collected)

  So to check if the dependency belongs to a dependency tree during collection
  we would need to traverse through both the collected and configured
  dependencies. While traversing through the collected packages we would need
  to mimic the pkg_configure*() logic in terms of selecting the prerequisite
  (pick the proper database, etc).

  After simulating of the plan execution, checking if the dependency is present
  in the dependency tree seems to be much more straightforward.

- During collection iteration the fact of (not) belonging of a dependency to
  the dependent's dependency tree may change in both direction, for example,
  due to upgrade of the constrained dependency's intermediate (in the tree)
  dependent. Such an upgrade may introduce or remove the constrained
  dependency to/from the constraining dependent's dependency tree (imagine
  that libbiz/2.0 in the previous example doesn't depend on libbuz).

- Need to accuratelly handle the following case:

  libfoo:
    depends: libbar <= 1.0 | libbaz

  foo:
    depends: libfoo
    constrains: libbar > 1.0 require {config.libbar.extras=true}

  $ bpkg build foo

  Here the applied dependency constraint effectively pushes libbar out of the
  dependent's dependency tree. As a result the constraint is in effect despite
  the fact that the respective dependency is out of the dependency tree.
  Should the config.libbar.extras configuration be applied in this case?
  Feels like it shouldn't. Also some efforts need to be applied to not start
  you-yoing. Probably we need to record states when we are about to mark a
  dependency constraint as not applicable (since dependency is not in the
  tree) and then re-collect. So that if we are in the same state next time, we
  do not re-collect or we re-collect in some special mode (apply version
  constrain, but not apply configuration to libbar and don't collect it
  recursively, etc). Although, would be nice to come up with something more
  simple.


Questions:

- Does constrains value support alternatives? No.

- Does constrains value support buildtime dependency? Seems like no harm in
  that. Feels like shouldn't complicate things.

- Does constrains value support multiple dependencies? What is the semantics
  if so (the constraint is applied if all dependencies are present in the tree
  or presence of any of them is sufficient, etc)? Probably make sence to only
  allow a single dependent for now, not to complicate things.

=============================================================================

When we simulated after the first pass, when we assume all the constraints
as inactive, we split all the constraints into 2 buckets:

1) Constraints for which the dependency appeared in the tree (but which we
   mistakenly skipped).

2) Constraints for which the dependency is not in tree (and which we skipped
   correctly).

Now we recollect the second pass using the first bucket as a reference to
consider constrains in effect. Those constrains which are not in the first
bucket, we skip. At the end of this pass we have a new set of constraints
which can (and normally does) overlap with a set of constraints obtained on
the first pass. We go through the new set of constraints and do the following:

1) If the constraint is new, we put it into the second bucket.
2) If it is old, leave them at old places???
3) Remove not existing now constraints from first and second buckets.

Now match constrains in buckets agains the reality and rebuild them (something
from the 1st bucket can go into the 2nd bucket and in the opposite direction
as well).

If the first bucket didn't change, then we are done. Otherwise, re-collect.
May start yo-yoing. To avoid that, track using hashes and fail if repeats.

As a separate step, handle corner case when constrain pushes out dependency
from the tree specially since it is likely fail preventing yo-yoing now
othrwise.

----------------------

Fix version replacement issue by tracking initiating dependents (with
constraints they apply) in the replaced version record in the map. When the
version is about to be applied, see if all the initiating dependents are still
there. If not, remove them and recalculate the desired version. Otherwise,
remove the record and recollect.

The problem with this approach is that at the time the version replacement
needs to be applied there is likely no the dependent yet, which initiated the
replacement.
